AUDIO: 'Insane paper today. This new work can delete stuff from your videos,&nbsp; but it does it in the right way. While many&nbsp;&nbsp; previous techniques fail at it. We have a bunch of puppies here,&nbsp;&nbsp; now let’s just have one, and remove&nbsp; the rest highlighted with blue. Previous technique from 2023. That is not great.&nbsp;'

[00:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This is a blurry mess, and it&nbsp; didn’t do the removal at all. Previous technique from 2025. Oh yes. Did it work?&nbsp;&nbsp; Yes and no. That’s a classic. True, the&nbsp; dogs are gone. But, are we done? Nope,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because not only the dogs need to be removed,&nbsp; but secondary effects like shadows too. Now let’s see the new technique. Look! Now we’re&nbsp; talking! It removed the shadows too for all of&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the frames, and it has done it well in each frame.&nbsp; Mess up just one, and we’ll easily find it. And by&nbsp;&nbsp; the end of this video, you will understand&nbsp; exactly how it does it. I’ll try my best.'

[00:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And if you’re a cat person, can it do that too?&nbsp; Wait wait wait, the interesting part here is not&nbsp;&nbsp; the cat. It is the movement of the grass blades.&nbsp; Look. The cat has some secondary effects too,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which need to be canceled out. Can it do that?&nbsp; Let’s see…oh my, it can. That is glorious. Okay, let’s make it even harder. The&nbsp; blinking colon is very easy to remove,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but you wise Fellow Scholars already know what is&nbsp; going on. Oh baby, glossy reflections. You have to&nbsp;&nbsp; remove those too. Can it? Yup. I am pixel peeping&nbsp; here, and I am not finding anything. Incredible.'

[01:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This new technique is called Omnimatte Zero&nbsp; and is a collaboration between NVIDIA and&nbsp;&nbsp; other labs. So Omnimatte Zero. Why Zero? Is&nbsp; this the number of frames per second we get?&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'No. I’ll tell you how slow or quick it is in&nbsp; a moment, it’s going to be pretty incredible. What about shadows that merge? The shadow of the&nbsp; bench has to remain, but the shadow of the person&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'has to go. There is no way anyone can pull that&nbsp; off, right? Well, this one can do that too, that&nbsp;&nbsp; is kind of insane. However, look. You pay for this&nbsp; by giving up some sharpness in the results. The&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'new one is a bit blurrier, and I think if I look&nbsp; closely, I can see some artifacts. Not perfect. Now here are the three incredible bombshells&nbsp; that almost made me fall out of the chair: one,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it uses already existing diffusion models. Two,&nbsp; it requires no additional AI training. And now&nbsp;&nbsp; hold on to your papers Fellow Scholars for three,&nbsp; it runs in real time. 25 frames per second. Wow.'

[02:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I didn’t even think this could&nbsp; ever be possible. So how is all&nbsp;&nbsp; this even possible? How do you&nbsp; do that? Let me try to explain.'

[03:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Dear Fellow Scholars, this is Two Minute&nbsp; Papers with Dr. Károly Zsolnai-Fehér. And while we talk about how it works. I’ll put up&nbsp; some uses cases that are not perfect so you can&nbsp;&nbsp; accurately see when it’s good and when it’s not so&nbsp; good. Very important to not overstate things here.'

[03:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Okay, so imagine your video is a stack of jigsaw&nbsp; puzzles. Each frame is one full puzzle. When we&nbsp;&nbsp; remove the dog, we are essentially removing a&nbsp; few puzzle pieces from the middle of the board.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'In the past, AI tried to paint a brand new piece&nbsp; to fill that hole. That is slow and often looks&nbsp;&nbsp; wrong. But this method, OmnimatteZero, realizes&nbsp; that the video is a sequence. Since we have a&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stack of puzzles, you can look at the one below&nbsp; or above yours that has the pieces missing. That&nbsp;&nbsp; is the video from one second ago or one second&nbsp; later. You don’t have to guess what is missing!&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Just find the exact piece that is&nbsp; missing now, and use that. Genius. And what is even more genius is that this explains&nbsp; all three of the bombshells we talked about. One, because it is finding and copying&nbsp; existing pieces rather than painting new&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ones from scratch, it doesn\'t need to go to&nbsp; art school. That is the zero training part.&nbsp; Two, it uses a standard puzzle builder that&nbsp; already exists - that is a pre-trained AI&nbsp;&nbsp; model that can create videos. Just take&nbsp; one off the shelf and plug that in.&nbsp;'

[04:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And three, most important of all: because copying&nbsp; a piece is instant compared to painting one,&nbsp;&nbsp; it runs in real time. It is beautiful in&nbsp; its simplicity. Absolutely loving this.'

[04:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Okay, but I hear you asking: but then&nbsp; why is the output footage blurrier than&nbsp;&nbsp; the input? Let’s pull up this equation&nbsp; and try to see the problem through that.'

[04:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This is a mathematical trick called mean temporal&nbsp; attention. Think of this as a magnet. The empty&nbsp;&nbsp; hole in our puzzle becomes magnetic. It pulls&nbsp; information only from the background pieces of&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[05:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the other puzzles in the stack. Now I just&nbsp; said mean temporal attention. Mean means&nbsp;&nbsp; average. So it averages these puzzles out to&nbsp; ensure the colors and lines match perfectly.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[05:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It forces the AI to look at the&nbsp; timeline, not just the single picture. So, why the blur on the bench and elsewhere?&nbsp; It comes back to that averaging part. Imagine&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[05:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the pieces the magnet pulls from the other&nbsp; puzzles are not perfectly aligned. Maybe the&nbsp;&nbsp; camera moved a tiny bit since then, or the&nbsp; compression algorithm added some noise or&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[05:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'artifacts. This means that the pixels change&nbsp; a bit over time, even on the same object. When you take five puzzle pieces that are just&nbsp; slightly offset from each other and smash them&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[05:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'together to create one average piece, the sharp&nbsp; lines get a little soft. If you average 1 and 9,&nbsp;&nbsp; you get 5. The extremes get blurred out.&nbsp; The fine texture also gets smoothed out.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This is the price we pay for stability.&nbsp; We trade razor-sharp details for a video&nbsp;&nbsp; that doesn\'t flicker. A fair trade if you&nbsp; ask me. And one that is almost guaranteed&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to be solved two more papers down the&nbsp; line. That is the First Law of Papers. Now, we are still not done yet. Not&nbsp; even close! We talked about how it&nbsp;&nbsp; would copy in pieces of a previous&nbsp; bench from earlier puzzle pieces,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that’s okay. But how does it know which&nbsp; shadow to keep and remove? Or how does it&nbsp;&nbsp; identify which blades of grass the cat has&nbsp; stepped on? That still sounds like witchcraft. Now there is another wonderful idea.&nbsp; You see, in a single photo - a single&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'puzzle - a shadow is just a dark patch of&nbsp; grass. But in a stack of puzzles, in video,&nbsp;&nbsp; the shadow moves with the dog. The AI realizes&nbsp; these pieces are magnetically stuck together.'

[07:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So just remove things that move together.&nbsp;&nbsp; Love it. A really advanced paper&nbsp; explained in really simple words.'

[07:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And whatever the test metric is, it sweeps all&nbsp; of these previous techniques like it wasn’t even&nbsp;&nbsp; a challenge. These are the two off the shelf&nbsp; open systems it is built on, you can plug in&nbsp;&nbsp; anything here, and it is a real hallmark of this&nbsp; new technique - look, the score highlights that&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[07:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it does not make a huge difference. Just&nbsp; plug in anything and it will make it work. The scientists behind it also promise&nbsp; that the source code of this will also&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[07:44] [scene:talk]
